<module>
  <title>toponymic proper nouns</title>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns are <a href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> which are also <a href="?xx=nouns/toponyms">toponyms</a>, i.e. they name places (geographical entities).</p>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns can be classified according to the kind of geographical entity they refer to –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>islands and districts eg. <m>Cataibh</m> <en>Sutherland</en>, <m>Barraigh</m> <en>Barra</en> <boxlink ref="#districts"/></li>
    <li>towns and settlements eg. <m>Glaschu</m> <en>Glasgow</en>, <m>Siabost</m> <en>Shawbost</en> <boxlink ref="#settlements"/></li>
    <li>countries and continents eg. <m>Alba</m> <en>Scotland</en>, </li>
  </ul>
  <p>Like other proper nouns, toponymic proper nouns can be modified by an attributive <u>adjective</u> eg. 
    <m>Alba Nuadh</m> <en>Nova Scotia</en>, <m>Sasainn Nuadh</m> <en>New England</en>, <m>Beàrnaraigh Mòr</m> <en>Great Bernera</en>,
    <m>Lodainn Meadhanach</m> <en>Midlothian</en>.</p>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns can be modified by one of the following four directional prepositional phrases –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>a Tuath</strong> <en>North(ern)</en> eg. <m>Uibhist a Tuath</m> <en>North Uist</en></li>
    <li><strong>a Deas</strong> <en>South(ern)</en> eg. <m>Uibhist a Deas</m> <en>South Uist</en>, <m>Afraga a Deas</m> <en>South(ern) Africa</en></li>
    <li><strong>an Ear</strong> <en>East(ern)</en> eg. <m>Ros an Ear</m> <en>Easter Ross</en>, <m>Lodainn an Ear</m> <en>East Lothian</en></li>
    <li><strong>an Iar</strong> <en>West(ern)</en> eg. <m>Ros an Iar</m> <en>Wester Ross</en>, <m>Lodainn an Iar</m> <en>West Lothian</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns can be modified by one of the following two directional adjectives –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Uachdarach</strong> <en>Upper</en> eg. <m>Pabail Uarach</m> <en>Upper Bayble</en>, <m>Canada Uachdarach</m> <en>Upper Canada</en></li>
    <li><strong>Ìochdarach</strong> <en>Lower</en> eg. <m>Pabail Iarach</m> <en>Lower Bayble</en>, <m>Canada Ìochdarach</m> <en>Lower Canada</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Toponymic proper nouns are used as roots for <a href="?xx=nouns/demonyms">demonyms</a> – 
    adjectives and common nouns describing or referring to a person (or other entity) originating from, 
    or otherwise associated with the place identified by the proper noun eg. <m>Leòdhasach</m> <en>(person) from Lewis</en>, 
    <m>Albannach</m> <en>(person) from Scotland</en>.</p>
  <p>[Glottonyms?]</p>
  
